Setting up Java on **Manjaro Linux** for running console apps is straightforward. 
Since Manjaro is Arch-based, you’ll use `pacman`.

---

## 1. Install Java (JDK)

Manjaro provides OpenJDK versions. 
Install a stable one (recommended: 17 or 21):


sudo pacman -S jdk21-openjdk

---

## 2. Verify Installation

java -version
javac -version

You should see version output.

---

## 3. Set Default Java (if multiple versions)

List installed JVMs:

archlinux-java status

Set default:

sudo archlinux-java set java-17-openjdk

---

## 4. Set JAVA_HOME (important for development)

Edit your shell config:

nano ~/.bashrc

Add:

export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk
export PATH=$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH

Apply:

source ~/.bashrc

---

## 5. Create and Run Console Java App

### Example: `Main.java`

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello from Java Console App");
    }
}

### Compile:

javac Main.java

### Run:

java Main

---

## 6. One-liner Run (quick testing)

echo 'class Main{public static void main(String[] a){System.out.println("Hi");}}' > Main.java && javac Main.java && java Main

---

